<subsection xml:id="subsec-drawing-bar-graphs-of-data-from-real-life-situations">
    <title>Drawing Bar Graphs of Data </title>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{red} \textbf{Work in groups}}</m>
        </p>
        
        <p>
            <ol marker="(i).">
               <li>Ask and record the number of members of your class, born in the months of January, February, March, April, May, and June.</li>
               <li><p>Fill in the table shown.</p>
                    <tabular halign="left" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium">
                        <row>
                            <cell>Month</cell>
                            <cell>Jan</cell>
                            <cell>Feb</cell>
                            <cell>Mar</cell>
                            <cell>Apr</cell>
                            <cell>May</cell>
                            <cell>Jun</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row>
                            <cell>No. of members</cell>
                            <cell> </cell>
                            <cell> </cell>
                            <cell> </cell>
                            <cell> </cell>
                            <cell> </cell>
                            <cell> </cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </li>
                <li>Choose a suitable scale and represent the data on a bar graph.</li>
                <li>Compare and discuss your graphs with other groups.</li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </activity>
    <p>
        <m>{\color{green} \textbf{Key Takeaway}}</m>
    </p> 
    <p>A bar graph is the display of information using rectangles of uniform width. The length of each rectangle represents the frequency.</p>
    <p>
        Bars can be displayed either vertically or horizontally and
        are used to compare different categories or groups.
    </p>
    <example>
        <statement>
          
            <p>
                The following table shows the number of learners who received different grades in an exam:
            </p>
            <tabular halign="left" top="medium" left="medium" right="medium" bottom="medium">
                <row>
                    <cell>Grade</cell>
                    <cell>Number of Learners</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>5</cell>
                    <cell>45</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>6</cell>
                    <cell>30</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>7</cell>
                    <cell>35</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>8</cell>
                    <cell>30</cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>9</cell>
                    <cell>40</cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
            <p>
                Choose a suitable scale and represent the data on a bar graph.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Choosing a suitable scale for the length of bars, for example 1cm representing 10 learner, the graph is drawn as shown.
            </p>
            <image>
                <latex-image label="a">
              
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                        \begin{axis}[
                            width=15cm, height=8cm,  % Increase size
                            ybar,
                            symbolic x coords={5, 6, 7, 8, 9},  % Use only numbers
                            xtick=data,
                            xlabel={Grade},
                            ylabel={Number of Learners},
                            ymin=0, ymax=50,  % Adjust based on your data
                            bar width=1.5cm,  % Adjust bar width
                            enlarge x limits=0.12,  % Space around bars
                            nodes near coords,  % Show values on top of bars
                            grid=both,  % Enable grid lines for both axes
                            major grid style={line width=0.5pt, draw=gray!50},  % Style for major grid lines
                            minor grid style={line width=0.2pt, draw=gray!25}  % Style for minor grid lines
                        ]
                            \addplot[
                                ybar,
                                fill=blue
                            ] coordinates {
                                (5, 45) (6, 30) (7, 35) (8, 30) (9, 40)
                            };
                        \end{axis}
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                
            </image>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <activity>
        <p>
            <m>{\color{red} \textbf{Further Activity}}</m>
